On 15 December 2006, discussions surrounding the Union State were reported to be intensifying [citation needed](/Wikipedia:Citation_needed). However, by January 2007, the talks appeared to have, shall we say, hit a snag. President [Alexander Lukashenko](/Alexander_Lukashenko) of [Belarus](/Belarus) made a rather pointed statement: "The Russian leadership is demanding that we join the Russian Federation—that's what is in the heads of the Russian leadership. I don't want to bury the sovereignty and independence of [Belarus]." He further elaborated, "From all the consultations and discussions, I have understood that we have different approaches and understandings of the building of a Union State," and explicitly opposed "the possibility of the incorporation into [Russia](/Russia) [of [Belarus](/Belarus)]." [67] A clear and unequivocal rejection of annexation, rather than integration.

Nevertheless, on 19 October 2007, Russian prime minister [Viktor Zubkov](/Viktor_Zubkov) announced that the budget of the Union State "will grow by no less than ten percent next year, and that growth will provide for worthy funding of our common projects." [68] This declaration sparked speculation that the Russian government had, once again, rekindled its interest in the concept of the Union State. Money, after all, often speaks volumes.

A high-profile meeting between President [Lukashenko](/Alexander_Lukashenko) of [Belarus](/Belarus), President [Vladimir Putin](/Vladimir_Putin) of [Russia](/Russia), and Union State Secretary [Pavel Borodin](/Pavel_Borodin) took place in [Minsk](/Minsk) on 13–14 December 2007. This gathering garnered considerable media attention and fueled renewed speculation that the Union State might indeed be the focal point of a fresh initiative from both governments. Of particular interest was the renewed discussion surrounding the Union Parliament (a body which, despite being planned, had never actually materialized) and a Union State Constitutional Act, a legal instrument that could, theoretically, significantly bolster the authority of the Union. According to State Secretary [Borodin](/Pavel_Borodin), five distinct variants of this Act were deliberated during the meeting, each of which envisioned a transitional period of 7 to 10 years for the Union's development. Trade and energy issues, naturally, were also on the agenda. [69]

On 27 May 2008, President [Lukashenko](/Alexander_Lukashenko), exercising his authority as Chairman of the Supreme State Council, appointed the then-Russian prime minister and current president, [Putin](/Vladimir_Putin), as chairman of the Council of Ministers. [70] This move, naturally, ignited further speculation that the Union was on the cusp of a significant political transformation. However, it's worth noting that the most visible, and arguably most influential, official within the Union has consistently been the State Secretary, who is responsible for managing the Union State's day-to-day operations. In the same meeting, State Secretary [Borodin](/Pavel_Borodin) announced that the 2009 Union State budget would amount to a sum of 6–7 billion [roubles](/Russian_rouble), representing a rather substantial increase of over 2 billion [roubles](/Russian_rouble) from the previous year, 2008.

On 1 August 2011, [Putin](/Vladimir_Putin) publicly stated his support for a union encompassing [Russia](/Russia), [Belarus](/Belarus), and potentially even [South Ossetia](/South_Ossetia). [71] However, this idea was swiftly rejected by [Belarusian](/Belarusian) foreign minister spokesman Andrei Savinykh [72], as well as by Dmitri Medojev, [South Ossetia's](/South_Ossetia) ambassador to [Moscow](/Moscow), who rather bluntly declared, "Our people voted for independence in a [referendum in 2006](/South_Ossetian_independence_referendum,_2006) and they do not relish the idea of becoming part of the Russian Federation." [72] It seems not everyone shared [Putin's](/Vladimir_Putin) expansive vision.

Since 2015, the primary focus for developing relations among former members of the [Soviet Union](/Soviet_Union) has shifted towards the ongoing development of the [Eurasian Economic Union](/Eurasian_Economic_Union) (EAEU). This entity itself represents a further evolution of the [Eurasian Customs Union](/Customs_Union_of_the_Eurasian_Economic_Union), which was originally established in 2010. The EAEU is explicitly modeled on the integration processes of the [European Union](/European_integration) and currently comprises 5 member states: [Belarus](/Belarus), [Russia](/Russia), [Kazakhstan](/Kazakhstan), [Armenia](/Armenia), and [Kyrgyzstan](/Kyrgyzstan). [Tajikistan](/Tajikistan) has also, rather tentatively, expressed an interest in joining [citation needed](/Wikipedia:Citation_needed). However, it is crucial to remember that the EAEU is, at its core, solely an [economic union](/Economic_union). Any aspirations for deeper political integration, for the time being, remain firmly within the purview of the Union State.

In 2021, renewed discussions among member states proposed deeper economic integration [73]. Subsequently, in November 2021, [Russia](/Russia) and [Belarus](/Belarus) formalized an agreement designed to establish common policies across a range of critical sectors, including taxation, banking, industry, agriculture, and energy. [74] A rather comprehensive attempt to weave their economies more tightly together.

2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine

Following the [2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine](/Russian_invasion_of_Ukraine), a conflict that notably saw part of its staging from [Belarus'](/Belarus) territory, both [Russia](/Russia) and [Belarus](/Belarus) found themselves subjected to a torrent of [international sanctions](/International_sanctions_during_the_2022_Russian_invasion_of_Ukraine) and widespread [boycotts](/2022_boycott_of_Russia_and_Belarus). On 3 March, [Belarusian president](/President_of_Belarus) [Alexander Lukashenko](/Alexander_Lukashenko) publicly affirmed his full support for [Russian president](/President_of_Russia) [Vladimir Putin's](/Vladimir_Putin) campaign in [Ukraine](/Ukraine), framing it as an integral part of [Belarus's](/Belarus) long-standing commitment to the Union State with [Russia](/Russia). [75] A rather stark demonstration of solidarity, or perhaps, obligation.

On 14 March, Russian prime minister [Mikhail Mishustin](/Mikhail_Mishustin) met with [Belarusian prime minister](/Prime_Minister_of_Belarus) [Roman Golovchenko](/Roman_Golovchenko) in [Moscow](/Moscow). Addressing reporters, [Mishustin](/Mikhail_Mishustin) stated that they had "coordinated measures to protect our economic security and the technological sovereignty of [Russia](/Russia) and [Belarus](/Belarus)" and further emphasized, "consider it necessary to strengthen integration in the Union State." [76] The sanctions, it seemed, only served to accelerate the perceived need for closer ties. On 18 March, the Russian government announced the lifting of all restrictions on the movement of citizens between [Russia](/Russia) and [Belarus](/Belarus). [77] And on 1 July 2022, [Russian President](/President_of_Russia) [Vladimir Putin](/Vladimir_Putin) himself declared that the "unification" process had been accelerated, with the explicit aim of mitigating the economic damage inflicted by the sanctions. [78]

In October 2022, in the aftermath of the [September 2022 mobilization of reservists in Russia](/2022_Russian_mobilization), a contingent of approximately 9,000 Russian soldiers arrived in [Belarus](/Belarus). According to the [Belarusian ministry of defence](/Ministry_of_Defence_of_Belarus), the stated purpose of this deployment was the creation of a "regional military grouping" of the Union State. [79] In the same month, it was announced that Russian air forces were actively patrolling the borders of the Union State in [Belarus](/Belarus). [80] The military aspect of the Union, it seems, was becoming increasingly prominent and active.

2023 nuclear deterrence

In a rather provocative interview aired by [Russia's](/Russia) state television in late May 2023, [Lukashenko](/Alexander_Lukashenko) made a striking declaration. He stated, quite matter-of-factly, that other countries willing to join the Union State would be offered nuclear weapons: "If someone is worried... (then) it is very simple: join in the Union State of [Belarus](/Belarus) and [Russia](/Russia). That's all: there will be nuclear weapons for everyone." [81] This statement came just days after he had confirmed the commencement of the movement of some of [Russia's](/Russia) tactical nuclear weapons to [Belarus](/Belarus). Furthermore, the Russian defence minister had previously confirmed the signing of documents outlining the procedure for storing tactical nuclear weapons in [Belarus](/Belarus) [82], a plan that [Putin](/Vladimir_Putin) had initially unveiled in March. [83] A clear, if somewhat unsettling, new dimension to the Union's potential offerings.

25th anniversary of the Treaty on the Creation of the Union State

On 6 December 2024, a date coinciding with the 25th anniversary of the Treaty on the Creation of the Union State, which was originally signed on December 9, 1999, a significant meeting of the Supreme State Council of the Union State took place. At this gathering, [Russian president](/President_of_Russia) [Vladimir Putin](/Vladimir_Putin) and his [Belarusian](/Belarusian) counterpart, [Alexander Lukashenko](/Alexander_Lukashenko), formalized an expansion of their defense and security cooperation. They did so by signing the Russia-Belarus Treaty on security guarantees within the Union State. [84] [85] [86] [87] This treaty, a quarter-century after the initial foundational agreement, marked a further, and rather pointed, deepening of their strategic alignment.

